 1st, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news-star.com/news/20191108/obu-selects-heath-thomas-as-universitys-16th-president|title=OBU selects Heath Thomas as university's 16th president|website=www.news-star.com|language=en|access-date=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Experience==\nTaylor previously served as president of [[Southwest Baptist University]] for 22 years.<ref name=\"President\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ncahlc.org/index.php?Action=ShowBasic&Itemid=192&instid=1465&option=com_directory|title=AQIP Institutions|accessdate=June 14, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"President2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mobaptist.org/am2008/article154528c1583780.htm|title=Taylor selected as 24th President of SBU|accessdate=June 14, 2018|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120804164856/http://www.mobaptist.org/am2008/article154528c1583780.htm#|archive-date=August 4, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Taylor was selected as the 24th president of [[Southwest Baptist University]] by the board of trustees on August 20, 1996, after a seven-month nationwide search. He assumed his duties as president on October 21, 1996. In January 2018, Taylor announced his retirement effective August 31, 2018 after nearly 22 years as University president.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sbuniv.edu/news-events/taylor-retirement-announcement.php|title=SBU President C. Pat Taylor announces upcoming retirement|website=www.sbuniv.edu|language=en|access-date=June 14, 2018}}</ref>\nTaylor returned to Oklahoma Baptist University to serve as interim president after the retirement of former president, David Whitlock. Heath Thomas replaced Taylor as president in January, 2020. \n\nPrior to becoming president of SBU, Taylor served as chief academic officer, senior vice president and provost at [[Oklahoma Baptist University]] in [[Shawnee, Oklahoma]] for ten years.  Taylor was responsible for OBU's academics, student development, admissions, religious life, library services and athletics from 1986 to 1996. \n\nTaylor previously served as associate vice president for academic affairs at [[Union University]] in [[Jackson, Tennessee]], from 1979 to 1986. From 1975 to 1979, he was an assistant professor of education at [[Belmont University]] in [[Nashville]], Tennessee. While at Belmont, he served as head resident of Pembroke Hall, a men's dormitory housing 150 men. His experiences also have included community college and high school teaching and coaching.<ref name=\"BIO\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sbuniv.edu/about/leadership/president.php|title=Dr. C. Pat Taylor {{!}} Office of the President {{!}} Southwest Baptist University|website=www.sbuniv.edu|accessdate=June 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nA native of [[Salem, Kentucky]], Taylor received his doctor of education degree with emphasis in history and philosophy of education from [[Memphis State University]]. He received a master's degree in history from [[Western Kentucky University]] and a bachelor's degree in history and secondary education from the [[University of Tennessee at Martin]].<ref name=\"BIO\" />\n\n==SBU highlights==\nAfter Taylor's arrival at SBU, the campus completed several major building and renovation projects including:\n*Jester Learning Center\n*University Grand Entrance\n*Meyer Wellness Center\n*Renovation of Taylor Free Enterprise Center\n*Renovation of Chapel\n*Renovation of Jim Mellers Conference Center\n*Plaster Athletic Facility\n*Allen Walk of Life <ref name=\"mbcpathway.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mbcpathway.com/otherstories/article58774.htm|title=SBU marks Taylor\u2019s 10th anniversary|date=November 10, 2006|accessdate=June 14, 2018}}</ref>\n*Major campus beautification and landscaping projects\n*Campaign fundraising of a $62,000,000 plus <ref name=\"mbcpathway.com\" />\n\n==Family==\nTaylor and his wife, Judy, were married in 1968 and have two children. Marijo is a 1994 [[Oklahoma Baptist University]] graduate and in 2000 received an Executive MBA from the [[University of Missouri]]. She is a